fields.name: Information Content Security
fields.description: Besides a local abuse of data and systems the information security can be endangered by a successful account or application compromise. Furthermore attacks are possible that intercept and access information during transmission (wiretapping, spoofing or hijacking). Human/configuration/software error can also be the cause.

fields.name: Intrusions
fields.description: A successful compromise of a system or application (service). This can have been caused remotely by a known or new vulnerability, but also by an unauthorised local access. Also includes being part of a botnet.

fields.name: Malicious Code
fields.description: Software that is intentionally included or inserted in a system for a harmful purpose. A user interaction is normally necessary to activate the code.

fields.name: Vulnerable
fields.description: Open resolvers, world readable printers, vulnerability apparent from Nessus etc scans, virus signatures not up-to-date, etc

fields.name: Application Compromise
fields.description: Compromise of an application by exploiting (un-)known software vulnerabilities, e.g. SQL injection.

fields.name: Login attempts
fields.description: Multiple login attempts (Guessing / cracking of passwords, brute force). This IOC refers to a resource, which has been observed to perform brute-force attacks over a given application protocol.

fields.name: Burglary
fields.description: Physical intrusion, e.g. into corporate building or data-centre.

fields.name: C2 Server
fields.description: Command-and-control server contacted by malware on infected systems.

fields.name: Data Loss
fields.description: Loss of data, e.g. caused by harddisk failure or physical theft.

fields.name: Distributed Denial of Service
fields.description: Distributed Denial of Service attack, e.g. SYN-Flood or UDP-based reflection/amplification attacks.

fields.name: DDoS amplifier
fields.description: Publicly accessible services that can be abused for conducting DDoS reflection/amplification attacks, e.g. DNS open-resolvers or NTP servers with monlist enabled.

fields.name: Denial of Service
fields.description: Denial of Service attack, e.g. sending specially crafted requests to a web application which causes the application to crash or slow down.

fields.name: New attack signature
fields.description: An attack using an unknown exploit.

fields.name: Harmful Speech
fields.description: Discretization or discrimination of somebody, e.g. cyber stalking, racism or threats against one or more individuals.

fields.name: Copyright
fields.description: Offering or Installing copies of unlicensed commercial software or other copyright protected materials (Warez).

fields.name: Availability
fields.description: By this kind of an attack a system is bombarded with so many packets that the operations are delayed or the system crashes. DoS examples are ICMP and SYN floods, Teardrop attacks and mail-bombing. DDoS often is based on DoS attacks originating from botnets, but also other scenarios exist like DNS Amplification attacks. However, the availability also can be affected by local actions (destruction, disruption of power supply, etc.) – or by Act of God, spontaneous failures or human error, without malice or gross neglect being involved.

fields.name: Exploitation of known Vulnerabilities
fields.description: An attempt to compromise a system or to disrupt any service by exploiting vulnerabilities with a standardised identifier such as CVE name (e.g. buffer overflow, backdoor, cross site scripting, etc.)

fields.name: Infected System
fields.description: System infected with malware, e.g. PC, smartphone or server infected with a rootkit. Most often this refers to a connection to a sinkholed C2 server

fields.name: Information disclosure
fields.description: Publicly accessible services potentially disclosing sensitive information, e.g. SNMP or Redis.

fields.name: Malware Configuration
fields.description: URI hosting a malware configuration file, e.g. web-injects for a banking trojan.

fields.name: Malware Distribution
fields.description: URI used for malware distribution, e.g. a download URL included in fake invoice malware spam.

fields.name: Masquerade
fields.description: Type of attack in which one entity illegitimately impersonates the identity of another in order to benefit from it.

fields.name: Misconfiguration
fields.description: Software misconfiguration resulting in service availability issues, e.g. DNS server with outdated DNSSEC Root Zone KSK.

fields.name: Outage
fields.description: Outage caused e.g. by air condition failure or natural disaster.

fields.name: Phishing
fields.description: Masquerading as another entity in order to persuade the user to reveal private credentials. This IOC most often refers to a URL, which is used to phish user credentials.

fields.name: Potentially unwanted accessible services
fields.description: Potentially unwanted publicly accessible services, e.g. Telnet, RDP or VNC.

fields.name: Privileged Account Compromise
fields.description: Compromise of a system where the attacker gained administrative privileges.

fields.name: Sabotage
fields.description: Physical sabotage, e.g cutting wires or malicious arson.

fields.name: Scanning
fields.description: Attacks that send requests to a system to discover weaknesses. This also includes testing processes to gather information on hosts, services and accounts. Examples: fingerd, DNS querying, ICMP, SMTP (EXPN, RCPT, ...), port scanning.

fields.name: Sniffing
fields.description: Observing and recording of network traffic (wiretapping).

fields.name: Social Engineering
fields.description: Gathering information from a human being in a non-technical way (e.g. lies, tricks, bribes, or threats).

fields.name: Unauthorised access to information
fields.description: Unauthorised access to information, e.g. by abusing stolen login credentials for a system or application, intercepting traffic or gaining access to physical documents.

fields.name: Unauthorised modification of information
fields.description: Unauthorised modification of information, e.g. by an attacker abusing stolen login credentials for a system or application or a ransomware encrypting data.

fields.name: Unauthorised use of resources
fields.description: Using resources for unauthorised purposes including profit-making ventures, e.g. the use of e-mail to participate in illegal profit chain letters or pyramid schemes.

fields.name: Undetermined
fields.description: The categorisation of the incident is unknown/undetermined.

fields.name: Unprivileged Account Compromise
fields.description: Compromise of a system using an unprivileged (user/service) account.

fields.name: (Child) Sexual Exploitation/Sexual/Violent Content
fields.description: Child Sexual Exploitation (CSE), Sexual content, glorification of violence, etc.

fields.name: Vulnerable system
fields.description: A system which is vulnerable to certain attacks. Example: misconfigured client proxy settings (example: WPAD), outdated operating system version, etc.

fields.name: Weak crypto
fields.description: Publicly accessible services offering weak crypto, e.g. web servers susceptible to POODLE/FREAK attacks.

fields.name: Deface
fields.description: Website defacement is an attack on a website that changes the visual appearance of a website or a web page

fields.name: Spam
fields.description: Or 'Unsolicited Bulk Email', this means that the recipient has not granted verifiable permission for the message to be sent and that the message is sent as part of a larger collection of messages, all having a functionally comparable content. This IOC refers to resources, which make up a SPAM infrastructure, be it a harvesters like address verification, URLs in spam e-mails etc.

fields.name: Other
fields.description: All incidents which don't fit in one of the given categories should be put into this class or the incident is not categorised.

fields.name: Bluekeep
fields.description: BlueKeep (CVE-2019-0708) is a security vulnerability that was discovered in Microsoft's Remote Desktop Protocol implementation, which allows for the possibility of remote code execution.

fields.name: HTTP Scanner
fields.description: Web Application Vulnerability Scanners are automated tools that scan web applications

fields.name: ICS Scanner
fields.description: ICS security is the area of concern involving the safeguarding of industrial control systems, the integrated hardware and software designed to monitor and control the operation of machinery and associated devices in industrial environments.

fields.name: Leak
fields.description: Information leakage allows an application to reveal sensitive data such as technical details of the application, developer comments, environment, or user-specific data.

fields.name: Local File Include
fields.description: Local File Inclusion (also known as LFI) is the process of including files, that are already locally present on the server, through the exploiting of vulnerable inclusion procedures implemented in the application

fields.name: SMBGhost
fields.description: Microsoft es consciente de una vulnerabilidad de ejecución remota de código en la forma en que el protocolo Microsoft Server Message Block 3.1.1 (SMBv3) maneja ciertas solicitudes. Un atacante que aprovechó con éxito la vulnerabilidad podría obtener

fields.name: Defacement
fields.description: Website defacement is an attack on a website that changes the visual appearance of a website or a web page
